The problem requires finding the probability that the maximum number of successes for one of the three drugs exceeds 8, given that each drug has a success probability of 0.7 and is tested in 10 independent trials (one per triple).

Since the success probabilities are equal and the assignments are random but identical in distribution, the number of successes for each drug follows a binomial distribution: Binomial(10, 0.7). The maximum number of successes exceeding 8 means that at least one drug has 9 or 10 successes.

First, compute the probability that a single drug has more than 8 successes (i.e., 9 or 10 successes):
- P(S = 9) = C(10,9) × (0.7)^9 × (0.3)^1 = 10 × 0.040353607 × 0.3 = 0.121060821
- P(S = 10) = C(10,10) × (0.7)^10 × (0.3)^0 = 1 × 0.0282475249 × 1 = 0.0282475249
- P(S > 8) = P(S = 9) + P(S = 10) = 0.121060821 + 0.0282475249 = 0.1493083459

The probability that a single drug has at most 8 successes is:
- P(S ≤ 8) = 1 - P(S > 8) = 1 - 0.1493083459 = 0.8506916541

Since the drugs are independent, the probability that all three have at most 8 successes is:
- P(all ≤ 8) = [P(S ≤ 8)]^3 = (0.8506916541)^3 ≈ 0.615623

The probability that the maximum exceeds 8 is the complement:
- P(max > 8) = 1 - P(all ≤ 8) = 1 - 0.615623 = 0.384377

Rounding to three decimal places (reasonable for the given inputs), the probability is 0.384.

