The lifetimes \(X_1\) and \(X_2\) are independent and identically distributed exponential random variables with mean \(\theta = 2\), so \(E[X_1] = 2\) and \(E[X_2] = 2\).  
Define \(Y_1 = \min(X_1, X_2)\) and \(Y_2 = \max(X_1, X_2)\). For two i.i.d. exponential random variables with mean 2, the minimum \(Y_1\) has an exponential distribution with mean \(E[Y_1] = \frac{\theta}{2} = \frac{2}{2} = 1\).  
The maximum \(Y_2\) satisfies \(Y_2 = X_1 + X_2 - Y_1\), so \(E[Y_2] = E[X_1] + E[X_2] - E[Y_1] = 2 + 2 - 1 = 3\).  
